---
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import Beats1 from "./_Beats1.astro";
import Beats2 from "./_Beats2.astro";
import Beats3 from "./_Beats3.astro";
import Beats4 from "./_Beats4.astro";
import Beats5 from "./_Beats5.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="Notes – Digitakt Beat Practice Ladder"
  description="Grounded drum-machine exercises: nail timing, density, and intention before complexity"
>
  <!-- article: a self-contained knowledge object; a page you could cite or export as-is -->
  <article id="beat-practice-ladder">
    <!-- header: introduction block for the page (title + framing) -->
    <header>
      <!-- h1: name of the page-level object; treat as a title, not a sentence -->
      <h1>Digitakt – Beat Practice Ladder</h1>

      <aside
        class="provenance-note"
        role="note"
        aria-label="Authorship and provenance note"
      >
        <span class="provenance-label">AI-generated text</span>
        <span class="provenance-text">
          Drafted with an AI system. Reviewed and edited by a human.
        </span>
      </aside>

      <p class="subtitle">
        A sequence of beat archetypes designed to build timing, pocket, and
        arrangement discipline before adding sound design, tricks, or "clever"
        modulation. Tailored to Digitakt MKI, but written to generalize to any
        groovebox.
      </p>
    </header>

    <!-- p: default unit of explanation; keep one idea per paragraph -->
    <p>
      The goal is not to collect patterns. The goal is to acquire a small set of
      reliable beat "moves" that you can execute cleanly at will. If a beat only
      works with heavy effects, complex probability, or happy accidents, it is
      not yet a skill. Start dry. Make it groove with velocity, microtiming, and
      restraint.
    </p>

    <p>
      Constraint for the whole ladder: keep the kit simple. One kick, one
      snare/clap, one closed hat, one open hat (optional), one percussion voice.
      If you want flavor, use sample choice and tuning first, then envelopes,
      then filters. Effects last.
    </p>

    <!-- nav: conceptual navigation; an index into the ladder -->
    <nav aria-label="Beat Ladder Index">
      <!-- ol: use when order matters (a ladder has a recommended sequence) -->
      <ol>
        <li><a href="#four-on-the-floor">Four-on-the-Floor Foundation</a></li>
        <li><a href="#backbeat">Backbeat and Pocket</a></li>
        <li><a href="#eighth-hats">Eighth-Note Hats and Dynamics</a></li>
        <li>
          <a href="#sixteenth-hats">Sixteenth Hats: Swing Without Slop</a>
        </li>
        <li><a href="#kick-variants">Kick Variants and Negative Space</a></li>
        <li><a href="#ghost-notes">Ghost Notes and Accents</a></li>
        <li><a href="#syncopation">Syncopation: Off-Grid Energy</a></li>
        <li><a href="#fills">Fills That Respect the Groove</a></li>
        <li><a href="#transition-bars">Transition Bars and Arrangement</a></li>
        <li>
          <a href="#performance">Performance: One Pattern, Many Moments</a>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </nav>

    <!-- section: major thematic grouping; keep headings shallow (h1–h3) -->
    <section id="beats">
      <!-- h2: stable category label -->
      <h2>Beats</h2>

      <Beats1 />
      <Beats2 />
      <Beats3 />
      <Beats4 />
      <Beats5 />
    </section>

    <!-- footer: closing material for the article -->
    <footer>
      <p class="text-muted">
        Keep this ladder editable. Add variations, but preserve the discipline:
        simplest viable kit, dry first, groove before tricks. When you add
        complexity, be able to explain what it buys you.
      </p>

      <nav aria-label="Related pages">
        <p class="text-muted">See also:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <a href="/ai-generated/patch-learn">Sound Design Practice Ladder</a> —
            the synth counterpart to this drum ladder
          </li>
          <li>
            <a href="/ai-generated/do-olls-that-will-talk/"
              >The Do-olls That Will Talk</a
            > — rhythmic timing analysis of a classic recording
          </li>
          <li>
            <a href="/ai-generated/sheev/">GoatTracker2 on macOS</a> — another angle
            on music tools
          </li>
        </ul>
      </nav>
    </footer>
  </article>
</Layout>
